definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 4-hydroxyphenyl group.
The trans-isomer of 2-coumaric acid.
A luteolin glucosiduronic acid consisting of luteolin having a beta-D-glucosiduronic acid residue attached at the 7-position.
A  benzenediol comprising of a benzene core carrying two hydroxy substituents ortho to each other.
A hexahydroxyflavone that is flavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3, 3', 4', 5, 5' and 7. It has been isolated from the leaves of Myrica rubra and other plants.
A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
A monohydroxycinnamic acid in which the hydroxy substituent is located at C-2 of the phenyl ring.
A tocopherol in which the chroman-6-ol core is substituted by methyl groups at positions 7 and 8. It is found particularly in maize (corn) oil and soya bean (soybean) oils.
An alpha-amino acid that is phenylalanine bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 4 on the phenyl ring.
The parent compound of the citrulline class consisting of ornithine having a carbamoyl group at the N(5)-position.
An aldopentose, found in the embryos of most edible plants and used in medicine to test for malabsorption by administration in water to the patient.
A phenylpropanoid that is an isomer of eugenol in which the allyl substituent is replaced by a prop-1-enyl group.
A glucan that consists of a backbone of alpha-(1->4)-linked glucose residues, most of which are substituted with (1->6)-linked xylose side-chains.
An alpha-amino acid that is glutaric acid bearing a single amino substituent at position 2.
Catechol in which the hydrogen at position 4 is substituted by a 2-aminoethyl group.
An alpha-amino acid that is pentanoic acid bearing two amino substituents at positions 2 and 5.
Any form of fucose having L configuration.
A class of aminophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of serine.
A monosaccharide derivative that is  hydroquinone attached to a beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 4 via a glycosidic linkage.
A C-glycosyl compound that consists of apigenin substituted by a 1,5-anhydro-D-glucitol moiety at position 6.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes carrying methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively.
A monomethoxybenzene that is 2-methoxyphenol substituted by a hydroxymethyl group at position 4.
A trihydroxyflavone that is flavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 4', 5 and 7.  It induces autophagy in leukaemia cells.
A glycosylfructose that is D-fructofuranose attached to a alpha-D-glucopyranosyl unit at position 6 via a glycosidic linkage. It is found in honey and sugarcane.

A methylcatechol carrying a methyl substituent at position 3. It is a xenobiotic metabolite produced by some bacteria capable of degrading nitroaromatic compounds present in pesticide-contaminated soil samples.
A phenol substituted at position 4 by a 2-hydroxyethyl group.
A member of the class of  phenols that is  styrene carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 4.

Xanthan gum is a polysaccharide produced by the bacteria Xanthomonas campestris. It is composed of pentasaccharide repeat units, comprising two glucose units, two mannose units, and one glucuronic acid unit. Its main chain consists of beta-D-glucose units linked at the 1 and 4 positions. Trisaccharide side chains contain a D-glucuronic acid unit between two D-mannose units linked at the O-3 position of every other glucose residue in the main chain. Approximately one-half of the terminal D-mannose contains a pyruvic acid residue linked via keto group to the 4 and 6 positions, with an unknown distribution. D-Mannose unit linked to the main chain contains an acetyl group at position O-6.
An inorganic calcium salt having silicate as the counterion.
A calcium salt that lacks C-H bonds
An organic calcium salt of stearic acid. It is a component of some lubricants and surfactants.
A magnesium salt that lacks C-H bonds
A magnesium salt with C-H bonds
A magnesium salt with C-H bonds
A phosphate salt that lacks C-H bonds
An inorganic potassium salt that is the tripotassium salt of phosphoric acid.
A phosphate salt with C-H bonds
A potassium salt that lacks C-H bonds
A beta-D-glucosiduronic acid having a 4-methylumbelliferyl substituent at the anomeric position. A hyaluronan synthesis inhibitor, it is  anti-tumourigenic for various malignant tumours.
A chromium salt that lacks C-H bonds
A chromium salt with C-H bonds
A copper salt that lacks C-H bonds
A copper salt with C-H bonds
A fluoride salt that lacks C-H bonds
A fluoride salt with C-H bonds
